    <div id="ncontentcolumn"> 
      <H1><!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Header" -->Introduction to Capital 
        Gains Tax<!-- InstanceEndEditable --></H1>
        <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="MainContent" --> 
        <p>Capital Gains Tax is a tax on the gain or profit you make when you 
          sell, give away or otherwise dispose of something. It applies to assets 
          that you own, such as shares or property. There's a tax-free allowance 
          and some additional reliefs that may reduce your Capital Gains Tax bill. 
          Sometimes you may have no tax to pay.</p>
        <p class="jumpListHead">On this page:</p>
        <ul class="jumpList">
          <li><a href="#1">What is Capital Gains Tax?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#2">Are all assets liable to Capital Gains Tax?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#3">Gifts, inheritance, divorce and Capital Gains Tax</a></li>
          <li><a href="#4">Working out your gains or losses</a></li>
          <li><a href="#5">The annual tax-free allowance</a></li>
          <li><a href="#6">Rates of tax on capital gains</a></li>
          <li><a href="#7">How to report a gain or loss</a></li>
          <li><a href="#8">Records you need to keep</a></li>
          <li><a href="#9">More useful links</a></li>
        </ul>
        <h2><a name="1"></a>What is Capital Gains Tax?</h2>
        <p> Capital Gains Tax is a tax on the profit or gain you make when you 
          sell or &#8216;dispose of&#8217; an asset.</p>
        <p> You usually dispose of an asset when you cease to own it - for example 
          if you:</p>
        <ul>
          <li> sell it</li>
          <li> give it away as a gift</li>
          <li> transfer it to someone else</li>
          <li> exchange it for something else </li>
          <li> receive compensation for it - for example you receive an insurance 
            payout when an asset's been destroyed </li>
        </ul>
        <p>It's the gain you make - not the amount of money you receive for the 
          asset - that's taxed.</p>
        <h3> Example</h3>
        <p> You bought some shares for &pound;2,500 in June 1990.</p>
        <p>You sell them for &pound;12,500 in May 2010.</p>
        <p>You've made a gain of &pound;10,000 (&pound;12,500 less &pound;2,500).</p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="2"></a>Are all assets liable to Capital Gains Tax?</h2>
        <p> Most assets are liable to Capital Gains Tax when you sell or dispose 
          of them - whether they're in the UK or overseas.</p>
        <p>However, some assets are exempt, such as your car, personal possessions 
          disposed of for £6,000 or less and, usually, your main home.</p>
        <p> <a href="when-to-pay.htm">Find out if your asset is liable to Capital 
          Gains Tax or exempt</a><!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="3"></a>Gifts, inheritance, divorce and Capital Gains Tax 
        </h2>
        <p>Many events can lead to a gain or loss, besides the obvious one of 
          selling an asset. A gain may sometimes occur when you least expect it.</p>
        <h3> Gifts</h3>
        <p>Making a gift to a child - or to other people or companies - is a ‘disposal’ 
          for Capital Gains Tax purposes. You'll need to work out if Capital Gains 
          Tax is due. However, making a gift to a spouse, civil partner or charity 
          usually won't lead to Capital Gains Tax.</p>
        <h3> Inheriting assets</h3>
        <p>If you inherit an asset, it’s not liable to Capital Gains Tax until 
          you sell or dispose of it. You’ll usually need to get a valuation of 
          the asset at the date of death, to work out the capital gain or loss. 
        </p>
        <h3> Divorce, separation or dissolving a civil partnership</h3>
        <p> When you divorce, separate or dissolve a civil partnership, you may 
          end up transferring assets between you. These are disposals for Capital 
          Gains Tax purposes. Whether you're liable depends on the date of transfer 
          and whether you&#8217;re living together at the time.</p>
        <p> <a href="gifts-inherit-divorce.htm">Find out more about how gifts, 
          inheritance and divorce affect Capital Gains Tax</a><!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="4"></a>Working out your gains or losses </h2>
        <p> When you sell or dispose of an asset, you need to work out the gain 
          or loss on each asset separately. You should include any allowable costs 
          associated with acquiring or disposing of the asset, and apply any tax 
          reliefs.</p>
        <p>Bring all the individual gains and losses together to work out the 
          gain or loss for the tax year and the amount of tax due.</p>
        <p> If you've got unused losses from earlier years - and have claimed 
          them in time - you may be able to deduct them too.</p>
        <p> You only have to pay Capital Gains Tax if you have overall gains above 
          the annual tax-free allowance (see the section below).</p>
        <p> <a href="working-basics.htm">Get more help with working out your capital 
          gain or loss</a> </p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="5"></a>The annual tax-free allowance </h2>
        <p> You have an annual tax-free allowance for Capital Gains Tax known 
          as the 'Annual Exempt Amount'. </p>
        <p>The Annual Exempt Amount for the tax year 2010-11 is:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>&pound;10,100 for each individual</li>
          <li>&pound;5,050 for most trustees</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The Annual Exempt Amount for the tax year 2011-12 is: </p>
        <ul>
          <li> £10,600 for each individual</li>
          <li> £5,300 for most trustees </li>
        </ul>
        <p>If your overall gains for the tax year are above the Annual Exempt 
          Amount, you&#8217;ll pay Capital Gains Tax on the excess.</p>
        <p> If your overall gains are below the Annual Exempt Amount, you won&#8217;t 
          pay Capital Gains Tax.</p>
        <h3> Example</h3>
        <p> Your overall gain in 2010-11 is £18,000.</p>
        <p> The Annual Exempt Amount is £10,100.</p>
        <p> You'll pay Capital Gains Tax on the excess of £7,900 (£18,000 - £10,100).</p>
        <h3>Trustees, executors/personal representatives </h3>
        <p>If you're a trustee or the personal representative of a deceased person’s 
          estate, use the link below to find out how to use the Annual Exempt 
          Amount.</p>
        <p> <a href="/rates/cgt.htm">More on tax-free allowances for Capital Gains 
          Tax</a></p>
        <h3>Non-UK residents</h3>
        <p>If you aren’t resident in the UK, please use the link below to find 
          out how to use the Annual Exempt Amount.</p>
        <p><a href="/rates/cgt.htm">More on tax-free allowances for Capital Gains 
          Tax</a></p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="6"></a>Rates of tax on capital gains </h2>
        <p>For 2009-10 Capital Gains Tax was charged at a flat rate of 18 per 
          cent.</p>
        <p>The same rate applied for 2010-11 up to 22 June 2010. </p>
        <p>From 23 June 2010 the following Capital Gains Tax rates apply:</p>
        <ul>
          <li> 18 per cent and 28 per cent for individuals (the tax rate you use 
            depends on the total amount of your taxable income and gains) </li>
          <li> 28 per cent for trustees or personal representatives </li>
          <li> 10 per cent for gains qualifying for Entrepreneurs' Relief </li>
        </ul>
        <p> <a href="/rates/cgt.htm">See Capital Gains Tax rates and annual tax-free 
          allowances</a></p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="7"></a>How to report a gain or loss</h2>
        <p>Once you've worked out that you have Capital Gains Tax to pay - or 
          a loss to claim - you must report it. If you haven't received a tax
           return or letter asking you to complete a tax return, you need to
          contact 
          HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC).</p>
        <p>If you normally complete a Self Assessment tax return, you need to 
          check if your gains need reporting (see the reporting link below). If 
          you have gains to report or a loss to claim, you'll need to complete 
          the additional Capital Gains Tax pages with your tax return.</p>
        <p> <a href="report-gain.htm">Find out more about reporting a capital 
          gain</a></p>
        <p> <a href="losses.htm">What to do if you&#8217;ve made a loss</a></p>
        <p><a href="http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kbroker/hmrc/contactus/search.ladv?raction=view&amp;fl0=__dsid%3A&amp;sm=0&amp;ha=34&amp;as=1&amp;sp_scope=hmrc&amp;sc=hmrc&amp;nh=10&amp;sr=0&amp;cs=ISO-8859-1&amp;tx1=&amp;tx0=49688">Telephone 
          or write to HMRC</a></p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="8"></a>Records you need to keep</h2>
        <p>It’s very important to keep any records about buying, selling or otherwise 
          acquiring or disposing of assets. You should also keep any records that 
          show your costs in relation to the asset. These will help you work out 
          the gain or loss and support your tax return or claim.</p>
        <p> <a href="record-keeping.htm">Find out more about record keeping and 
          Capital Gains Tax</a></p>
        <!-- #BeginLibraryItem "/Library/wcp-top.lbi" --><p class="gotoTop"><a href="#top" >Top</a></p><!-- #EndLibraryItem --> 
        <h2><a name="9"></a>More useful links</h2>
        <p><a href="../property/index.htm">Property and Capital Gains Tax</a></p>
        <p><a href="../shares/index.htm">Shares and Capital Gains Tax</a></p>
        <p><a href="../possessions/index.htm">Personal possessions and Capital 
          Gains Tax</a></p>
        <p><a href="../businesses/index.htm">Capital Gains Tax for businesses</a></p>
        <p><a href="/cgt/trusts.htm">Trusts and Capital Gains Tax</a></p>
        <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></div>
